```dotfiles/zed/Library/Application Support/Zed/.gitkeep#L1-60
# .gitkeep placeholder for the "zed" GNU Stow package
#
# Purpose:
# - Keep this directory structure in the repository so it can act as a Stow package
#   for Zed editor user settings.
# - Place Zed user files here so Stow can create symlinks into:
#     ~/Library/Application Support/Zed/
#
# Typical files to add in this directory:
# - settings.json
# - keymap.json
# - snippets/ (folder with snippet files)
# - extensions/ or other Zed-specific folders you want tracked
#
# Example repository layout (for this package):
# dotfiles/
# └── zed/
#     └── Library/
#         └── Application Support/
#             └── Zed/
#                 ├── settings.json
#                 └── keymap.json
#
# How to stow (from the repo root):
# - Default (run from repo root, target is $HOME):
#     stow -v --target="$HOME" zed
#
# - Or explicitly specify the package directory (-d) and target (-t):
#     stow -v -d /path/to/repo -t "$HOME" zed
#
# - Use dry-run to preview changes before applying:
#     stow -n -v -t "$HOME" zed
#
# Notes:
# - If files already exist at the target location, back them up before stowing
#   or use the repository bootstrap script which handles backups.
# - Keep this placeholder so the directory structure is preserved in git.
#
# When you add real files, remove or replace this placeholder with the actual files
# you want tracked (settings.json, keymap.json, etc.).
